</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utormentcia.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tormentcia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 106<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/27/01 5:41:22 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Clerics-Peridots and You (open discussion)</span><hr size=1> Actually, for the past few months, I've taken to regularly carrying around at least one stack of peridots, for a number of reasons.  I originally started doing so because I had started raiding on Planes and noticed clerics/enchies would run out if we were there for a long period of time, so I thought a back up plan would be good.  <br>
<br>
Aside from raiding, I decided to carry them in general because of the grouping situation and clerics/enchies need them for buffs.  Granted, enchies not as much as the clerics, but they still need them for certain situations.  I wanted to have them to provide if they ran low or just didn't get the reimbursement from gem drops.  I always make it a practice to tell the group cleric/enchie that I have peridots for their use if they need them, and no I don't charge them .. they're for the betterment of the group afterall.<br>
<br>
The final reason I carry them is for the times I will inevitably need a rez and there are no clerics in my group or I do something stupid and am not in a group at all.  I figure it's a bit more of a thoughtful &quot;donation&quot; than platinum and it saves the cleric the trip to the merchant for a little while longer.  As a friend put it to me once, receiving peridots vs. platinum for a rez is the difference between the gift you want at Christmas and just cash. <p>Tormentcia

